    description_en:
      'Boro rice, known as "boro dhan" or simply "boro" in Bengali, is a high-yielding variety of rice cultivated in Bangladesh. It is one of the three major rice varieties grown in the country, alongside aus and aman rice. Boro rice is typically cultivated during the dry season, from November to April. Boro rice cultivation involves advanced agricultural practices, including land preparation, seedbed preparation, transplanting, irrigation, and pest management. Unlike aus and aman rice, boro rice is grown in irrigated lowland areas, where water availability is ensured through irrigation channels, tube wells, or other means. Farmers often use modern machinery such as transplanters and harvesters to improve efficiency and productivity. Transplanting of boro rice seedlings usually takes place in December or January, depending on local growing conditions. The rice plants grow vigorously during the dry season, benefiting from ample sunlight and irrigation water. Harvesting of boro rice typically occurs around four to five months after transplanting, usually in April or May. Boro rice is known for its high yield potential and superior grain quality, making it a preferred choice for both farmers and consumers. It is used to make various rice-based dishes, including plain rice, pulao, biryani, and fried rice. Boro rice cultivation significantly contributes to food security and economic prosperity in Bangladesh, providing employment opportunities and income for millions of people involved in the rice value chain.',
