      'Aman rice, known as "aman dhan" or simply "aman" in Bengali, is a variety of rice widely cultivated in Bangladesh. It is one of the three major rice varieties grown in the country, alongside aus and boro rice. Aman rice is typically cultivated during the monsoon season, from June to November.Traditional farming methods are employed for Aman rice cultivation, including land preparation, sowing, irrigation, and pest management. Aman rice is often grown in rain-fed lowland areas, where water availability is dependent on seasonal rainfall. Farmers may use organic fertilizers and minimal chemical inputs to maintain soil fertility and ensure a healthy crop.Harvesting of Aman rice typically occurs around five to six months after planting, depending on the variety and local growing conditions. Once the Aman rice plants reach maturity, they are harvested manually using sickles or other hand tools. The harvested rice grains are then threshed to separate them from the stalks and dried in the sun.Aman rice is a staple food in Bangladesh and is used to make various culinary dishes, including rice-based meals such as biryani, khichuri, and rice pudding. It is valued for its distinct flavor, aroma, and texture, making it a preferred choice for traditional Bangladeshi cuisine. Aman rice cultivation plays a crucial role in ensuring food security and livelihoods for millions of people across the country.',
